---
description: React component decomposition, shared logic, and theme ownership
globs: frontend/src/**/*.{js,jsx}
alwaysApply: false
---

# Component size and layout

- One React component per file. Components that exceed ~250 lines must
  be decomposed into feature-folder siblings. Historical example:
  `ChatList.js` was 670 lines and now lives in `components/chat-list/`
  split into `ChatList`, `SearchBar`, `EmptyState`, `ProjectGroup`,
  `ChatCard`. Contemporary example: `AppContextMenu.js` was 268
  lines and now delegates its save/restore selection state to the
  `useSavedSelection` hook and its DOM helpers (`isEditableElement`,
  `findSelectionContainer`) to `utils/dom.js`, leaving the component
  at ~180 lines of handlers + `<Menu>` JSX.
- Duplicated UI across pages (dialogs, toolbars, cards) is extracted
  into `components/<shared-area>/`. The export format + warning
  dialogs lived twice in the codebase before the refactor and must
  never again.

# Shared logic and helpers

- Duplicated logic across pages (fetch + cancel effects, cookie
  read/write, event state machines, selection save/restore) lives in
  `src/hooks/`. Current examples: `useChatSummaries`, `useExportFlow`,
  `useExportWarningPreference`, `useSavedSelection`. Hooks have
  additional discipline of their own — see
  [frontend-hooks.mdc](frontend-hooks.mdc).
- Pure helpers (`formatDate`, `dbPathLabel`, cookie parsing, DOM
  inspection) live in `src/utils/`. A helper may not be copied into
  two components; promote it on sight.

```jsx
// Wrong: duplicated at the top of ChatCard and ChatMetaPanel
function formatDate(date) { /* ... */ }

// Right
import { formatDate } from '../../utils/formatDate';
```

# Theme ownership

- MUI theme tokens (`palette`, `sx`) own the visual language. CSS
  files in `src/` must **not** hard-code colors the theme already
  controls. Keep global CSS limited to font stacks, CSS-variable-
  driven scrollbars, and purely structural concerns. Motivating
  example: `frontend/src/index.css` previously hard-coded `#2D2D2D`
  for `pre` and `code` even in light mode.
- Contexts (`ColorContext`, `ThemeModeContext`) are defined in
  `src/contexts/`, one per file. Do not re-export contexts from
  `App.js`; import them from their defining file.

# Effects and export flow

- Use a cancellation flag
  (`let cancelled = false; ... return () => { cancelled = true; };`)
  for every `useEffect` that awaits a network request, and respect it
  after every `await` boundary.
- Reuse the `useExportFlow` hook for any new "export to file" UI
  rather than copying the format-dialog -> warning-dialog ->
  `exportChat()` state machine again.

# Third-party imperative-DOM libraries

When integrating a library whose primary output is imperative DOM mutation
(mermaid, prism, monaco, etc.), isolate it behind a dedicated React
component that owns the `useEffect` + cleanup, and a companion hook that
manages the library's global singleton (initialization, theme sync).
**Never** call the library's `.initialize` / `.render` / singleton-setup
function directly inside a React render function — only inside effects.

`MermaidBlock` + `useMermaid` are the canonical example:

- `useMermaid` (in `frontend/src/hooks/useMermaid.js`) owns
  `mermaid.initialize` — called in a `useEffect([darkMode])` once at the
  `MessageMarkdown` level so the singleton is always configured before any
  block renders.
- `MermaidBlock` (in `frontend/src/components/MermaidBlock.js`) owns the
  per-block async `mermaid.render` call, the diagram/source toggle state,
  the `latestRef` cancellation pattern (per
  [`frontend-hooks.mdc`](frontend-hooks.mdc)), and the error fallback UI.
  It also re-initializes mermaid immediately before each `mermaid.render`
  call because React runs child effects before parent effects, so the
  parent's `useMermaid` effect may not have run yet on the first mount.
